Monday, January 25, 1926

To Lakeside, Ramona, San Pasqual, Escondido. Miles 95. Clear warm weather. Start 2:30. Return 6:15. With Chickering, Peckham, Fowler. Did not stop by the roadside at any point.

One yearling Pituophis catenifer annectens at upper end of San Pasqual Valley.

Notes:

cassieswindle

Would you prefer P. catenifer annectens be linked to P. catenifer, or kept as its own link?

cassieswindle

Linked 3 different people, unsure of Expert/Family/Friend status.

lwilliams

Yes, just as P. catenifer

Sunday, February 21, 1926

Went to Mission Valley with Philip and Gartz. Started at 2 PM; returned at 4:30. A warm clear day. Total distance 16 miles.

Saw no snakes or lizards. Went down 6th St grade; returned on Farimont.

Went up the river to foot of Mission Gorge i.e. where river emerges. Found plenty egg strings of Bufo boreas halophilus. Mostly in shallow pools where there was no water flow. Many pools had none but where they were present there were large quantities. They were apparently quite fresh. In some places there were masses which were further developed, movement being evident. In these cases could not be sure they were the same species as the strings were broken up but judged from partially dried strings along the margin that all were bufo. Brought home two jars full.

Caught one large hyla regilla but lost him.

Notes:

cassieswindle

Do you want streets linked? Just making sure.

cassieswindle

For the second bufo link, didn't know if you wanted that actually linked to Anaxyrus, assuming it would be the same species and then considering the name change? Left as bufo.

Saturday, February 27, 1926

At 3:05 PM went to Mission Gorge where hunted awhile; thence to Santee and returned by highway. With Philip. A clear hot day, the third of a series. Yesterday 87 degrees. Humidity low. Returned at 6:05. Total miles 30.

In the gorge found many of the pools dried up and the bufo eggs likewise. Elsewhere the eggs had all hatched and the tad poles were congregated in great numbers where the water was still and shallow. Saw no unhatched live eggs. Collected a jar of tad poles. Saw one large grey tadpole different from the black bufos.

Saw no live snakes or frogs.

Saw 2 S. orcutti's in the gorge one being young. Also 1 uta. s. h.. One other lizard undetermined . Did not collect any.

One large gopher snake dead by the roadside just above the gorge.

Sunday, February 28, 1926

To the top of the grade beyond Glen Lonely via Encanto Helix Grossmont Bostonia Dehesa. Returned via Alpine Junction, Alpine and the highway. Started at 10:15. Returned at 6 PM. With Family and Harriet C. Miles 86.6. The fourth hot day of a series. Ate lunch at Glen Lonely. Stopped to hunt at three places only via Glen Lonely, at top of grade beyond school, and for a short time on Dehesa grade. Saw plenty lizards particularly crossing the road.

Got 2 Xantusias 1 large 1 small at top of Glen Lonely grade. Saw several more.

Got a fine large mitchelli at Glen Lonely in the rocks above the school. Was coiled in resting pose to south of moderate sized rock that had a hollow beneath. In this he took refuge at once. Looked as if it might have been his den. Was quite lively and difficult to catch.

One dead juveline Pituophis at Lakeview.

Notes:

cassieswindle

Do you want mitchelli linked to C. mitchellii, or C. mitchellii pyrrhus?

lwilliams

Just as C. mitchellii... no sub species

Sunday, March 7, 1926

To El Monte Oaks. Started at 11:20. Went via Fairmont and Mission Gorge. A clear moderately warm day in town after a week of similar weather. Family, Gartz, HKs, MKs. Wangs. Werts etc.

Stopped for lunch at El Monte Oaks but almost immediately a shower started. Got quite heavy. Finally had to leave.

Went back to Lakeside where there had been almost no rain. Then around to Lakeview where a stop for the afternoon was made. Hunted all afternoon in the rocks along the cliffs east of the road between Lakeside and Lakeview. Returned at 6:30. Total miles 60.

1 dead Pacific Rattler large in Mission Gorge.
1 live alligator caught in Mission Gorge.
1 large M. lateralis lost in Mission Gorge.
1 medium gopher caught in Mission gorge.
1 large Pacific Rattler dead in road at El Monte.

Above Lakeside caught the following.

1 large alligator
1 Xantusia henshawi.
1 Skelly (male

Saw several skellys & Utas.

Friday, March 12, 1926

Alligator lizards at 25.9, 26.9 and about 15.

Saturday, March 13, 1926

Went out with Philip in the afternoon. Start at 2:15; back at 6:30. Previous day had very hot with east wind but today was only comfortably warm. Rather overcast and cloudy in the back country. Total miles 69. Went to Dulzura summit; out Cajon Ave, return via Encanto.

One dead yearling gopher near top of grade before descending into Jamacha. On Jamul grade 16.4 got one yearling gopher crossing the road. Further down the same grade got a 5 rattle red rattler. Was on edge of road. No fight.

First stopped to hunt in large cactus patch beyond Jamul. Got a fair sized red rattler. He was in cactus and rattled before I saw him just as I passed 8 to 10 ft away. First appearance of this kind.

Next hunt was in rocks and cactus at bend in road. Got 2 skellys here and lost 1 horned toad. No snakes.

One dead yearling gopher just beyond first crossing of Dulzura Creek.

Last hunt at Dulzura summit. Got 1 fine large red rattler. Was stretched out and moving slowly along base of rocks. Also 1 X. h. Also 1 yearling Pacific rattler dead in the road. 33.9. Got 2 alligator lizards. Lost 1 ??)

Notes:

cassieswindle

Last word of entry=??

Sunday, March 14, 1926

Went to Viejas on a large family picnic. Everybody along including Ed, Werts and Wallenbergs. Start at 11:15 back at 6:10. A moderately warm day - somewhat cloudy. Went out by highway; returned via Alpine, Dehesa, Jamacha, Encanto.

No dead snakes seen in the road. Hunted in two places at foot of Viejas grade just north of large oaks where picnicked and on both sides of the road near old reservoir. Got nothing in the second place.

In the first got a skink and skelly. Not many lizards were seen this day; mostly skellys.

In large pile of rocks got 2 large red rattlers. First saw tail of one draped over rock about 15 feet away. Found this snake half under a large flat rock and another coiled within. They were extricated with considberable difficulty.

One escaped from sack while other was being placed therein and having been severely mauled the first time was ready for a fight. When cornered in a bush with a rock at his back he struck viciously once about half his length. Neither did anything but attempt to escape while under the original rock.

Saturday, March 20, 1926

Went to the Dulzura Creek just beyond the first crossing, with Philip, V.A. Lyman and his mexican nephew. Started at 1 P.M.; returned at 6 P.M. Total miles 57.7. A cloudy day, rather cool. Occasional sun. Evidently rain in mountains beyond.
1 dead Juvenile gopher at 15. Jamul.
1 dead do at 15.5 " "
1 Pacific Rattler about 5 rattles complete. Caught crossing the road at 19 Jamul.
1 dead Juvenile Boa at 22.7. Jamul.
No other snakes seen in the road dead or alive, coming or going.
Hunted at only one place - namely at 28.9 miles just beyond Dulzura Creek crossing. Hunted on rocky hillside to north of road. Got 1 Siagonodon humilis under rock flake, 1 - 5 Rattle exsul (Lyman). Lyman also saw a snake which escaped probably M. Lateralis but can't be counted. Got following lizards. 15 Xh (lost 8) 1 Uta 1 Skelly, 1 Coleonyx. Saw only one other lizard; they were quite scarce today. Too cold. Xh's are quite evidently under thin flakes and on south sides.

Sunday, March 21, 1926

Went up Cottonwood Creek about 2 mi. n. of the store (junction point). Out via Encanto; returna via La Mesa. Total miles 81.2. With family, Alice K. + Harriett. Cool and slightly windy. Rain at Barrett (reported). Part cloudy at cottonwood. Started at 10:45; returned at 6:00 P.M. Met HKs there.
Hunted in rocky hillside before lunch. Climbed difficult cliff after lunch. Used very poor judgment here as used all time and strength climbing this and it was too steep for snakes. Never again.
In these rocks got 3 Utas, 1 Hyla arenicolor 1 Batrachoseps (HK). Saw a number of Utas and Skellies No Orcuttis. Alice caught one toad at camp.
Snakes: On road about a mile west of Dulzura lost a garter in the poison oak. At this point one dead Trimorphodon partly smashed and decomposed but saved him anyway.
At Spring Valley 1 dead gopher about 1/2 grown in the road.
A rotten day (except the Trimorphodon) and my own fault

Saturday, March 27, 1926

Went to Dulzura Summit with Philip. Start at 1:30; returned at 6 P.M. went by regular road and returned by way of hill road to Jamacha. A partly cloudy moderate day; neither warm nor cold. Total miles 69.
Hunted for a short time at the cactus patch between Jamacha and Jamul but got nothing.
Dead snakes on the road 2; both young Gophers at 19.4 and 22.6 miles (Jamul).
Spent the rest of the time hunting at Dulzura Summit. Got one red rattler. Was unusually thin. Looked almost sick. He saw me first and rattled lightly and hissed; took the striking attitude at once. Was about five feet away when first seen. (Died in 12 days)
Got 2 Utas, 2 Skellys, 1 horned toad, 1 Hyla arenicolor (under a Xantusia flake) and 1 Xantusia all at this point. 1 Uta with eggs. Lizards were rather plentiful and I saw many I did not get; amongst others at least half a dozen S. orcuttis.

Sunday, March 28, 1926

Went to Wildwood via Mission Gorge; returned via highway. With Goulds (exc. E.B.) and family started at 10:45; returned around 6 P.M. A cloudy cold day with little sunshine and a strong west wind particularly evident at the higher elevations. Total miles 67.
Saw no dead snakes on the highway.
On the way out got me California King about half grown crossing the road at Mission Gorge. This was the only snake seen on the road.
Hunted at Wildwood on east mountain both before and after lunch. Was much troubled by brush. Wind was bad particularly in the afternoon except under lee of hill.
Lizards: got 17 X.h. (lost many) 1 Uta 1 skink. Saw 1 horned toad; 1 Skelly orcutti. Not many lizards running about.
Snakes got one Siagonodon humilis under a flat rock. Earth below; not another rock. Got a good boa Found with head and 1/3 of body under a flat rock; balance showing. Had a short tail; no orange color.
Found a large M. lateralis under a flake (typical X.h. flake about 45 degree angle and thin.) was coiled up under middle fully 9' above ground. Eye quite opaque. Lost him. See next sheet.

Saturday, April 3, 1926

Traveled 108 miles alone. 6th St grade, Murphy Canyon, Escondido, San Marcos, Twin Oaks, San Marcos, Vista, San Luis Rey River (south side) Oceanside, Rose Canyon. Start at 2 P.M. - Returned at 6:10.
A cool partly cloudy day after a week of similar weather. Quite windy. Did not stop to hunt at any point.
Got one live snake; a very large Thamnophis in the creek bed at Escondido on the short cut west of the town.
Checked the following dead snakes
Pituophis large Mission Valley
do small Poway grade
do do Escondido
do large San Marcos
Thamnophis medium do
Pituophis large Del Mar
C. exsul do Rose Canyon
Pituophis do do
do do do
Rhinocheilus do Pacific Beach (or Morena)

Sunday, April 4, 1926

Went to Borrego Valley with Philip, Ayres, Weiss and C.D. Jr. Travelled 195.2 mi. Went out via Sutherland; returned via the south road between Ballena and Ramona Otherwise shortest roads. Started at 7:30; returned at 8:20 P.M
At the start the weather was partly cloudy but not cold. Very windy in San Felipe. Comfortable in Yaqui Well, Narrows, and Borrego Valley; still partly cloudy. Returning ran into a heavy mist between Banner and Julian. This became a heavy rain at Witch Creek and quite a storm from Ramona in. Couldn't have seen a snake on the road alive or dead from Witch Creek in x. Saw a few toads hopping across the road by the head lights.
Only one live snake seen. This was a small gopher caught at the top of Mussey grade (34.1 mi)
Only 2 dead snakes seen; 1 large gopher at 37.1 (top of Mussey) and 1 large patch nose 5.3 mi east of Julian on the way home. Call it Banner as it was way below first trees.
Hunted for a short time at the Narrows on the way out. Got 1 Callisaurus ventralis ventralis.
Then hunted for a long time at Borrego amongst the mesquite but got one Uta.

<strike>Monday</strike>, April 5, 1926

Sunday (Continued)

graciosa. Just before reaching Borrego (that is where we stopped) got a Crotaphytus wislizenii (with 2 eggs) and a Dipsosaurus dorsalis dorsalis.
Last hunt was at foot of Sentenac. By this time it was quite windy, dark and cold. Got 1 Uta stansburiana elegans under a granite flake. Turned over many rocks here and at the Narrows but got nothing.
As in the case of the previous trip in May of last year I was impressed with the scarcity of reptile life in the desert. Lizards were exceedingly scarce.
In Borrego Valley met a rancher who had lived there 12 years althrough now farming at Coachella. Talked snakes. It was quite evident he could distinguish between C. exsul, C. oreganus, C. atrox atrox, and C. cerastes. He had never seen any rattlers but C. cerastes in Borrego Valley. Claimed to be familiar with C. atrox atrox from Imperial and Coachella. Said they were more numerous in Coachella than Imperial.
C. cerastes quite plentiful in Borrego he thought especially in May and September.

<strike>Tuesday</strike>, April <strike>6</strike>, 1926

Sunday April 4th continued

Said they could be caught most easily under bushes after showers.
He said there were gopher snakes in the valley-not many. They were the desert kind light colored with fewer spots.
Also there were red racers.
There was another snake which he referred to as a King snake - as near as I could judge is the yellow phase of the red racer
Some mileages
Ramona 41.9
Julian 64.6 22.7 via Sutherland
Borrego 98.1 (turned back)
Narrows 106.2
Julian 132.0 21.8 via South Road
Ramona 153.8
Home 195.2

Saturday, April 10, 1926

Has rained from Sunday the 4th to Friday the 9th continuously. Almost 5.5" of rain in San Diego and from 2.5" to 12.5" throughout the county.
This day was cool and part cloudy. Went to Point Loma, Mission Beach, La Jolla, Pacific Beach with GG & Rickey Sart at 3:30 - returned at 6 P.M. Did not get out to hunt. Saw no snakes on the road dead or alive. 46 miles total.

Sunday, April 11, 1926

A cool partly cloudy day. Rather cold wind. Very damp ground in the back country.
Went to Ramona with family and Stell. Start at 10:30; returned at 6 P.M. 82 miles
Picnicked just beyond Ramona on Sutherland Road where there are many rocks on the north side. Hunted here only.
Saw no snakes along the road dead or alive.
While I was hunting in the rocks the family got one large C. oreganus.
Almost stepped on in the bush.
Found one L. roseofusca large under a small flat rock. Only snake I saw.
Got 2 X.h. and one U.s.h.. Saw few lizards. Lost a few X.h. Saw one orcutti under a rock but lost him.
The rocks at this Ramona location are no good. Not the right consistency to flake.

Sunday, April 18, 1926

A cold windy day threatening rain. 140 miles
Went to Campo via southern route then to White Eagle garage and returned via Descanso Highway. Started at 10:30; returned at 7 P.M. with family, Allie & Harriett. Stopped for lunch west of high railroad bridge. Hunted in the rocks here for almost one hour. Did not hunt at any other place.
Did no see any live snakes this day.
Caught 3 Skellys, 1 Uta, 1 Xantusia at lunch place. Also shot one orcutti. Saw several lizards which I did not get, but not of any other kinds.
Only 2 dead snakes on the road showing that they had not ben out during the week:
1 Juvenile gopher at Encanto (5 mi).
1 Patch nose at Potrero (50 mi).
Had plenty car trouble this trip. Seemed to be stoppage in the gasoline feed. Rained all the way on the return trip. Turned out to be bad coil.

Saturday, April 24, 1926

A cool day with a high fog in town; warm and sunny in the back country.
Went to foot of Old Viejas Grade via La Mesa, Grossmont, Bostonia (south side), Dehesa, Alpine, Willows (picked up Allen here). Returned by the highway.
Did not hunt at any time. Started at 1:30; returned at 6 P.M. Total miles 78
Plenty lizards along the road, skellys and utas.
Live snakes
1 large M. lateralis crossing the road at Dehesa
1 small M. lateralis crossing the road on the Dehesa grade. Lost both of these.
Dead snakes
1 large T. o. hammondii in the highway near enterance of Harbison Canyon road

Sunday, April 25, 1926

A cool day with a high fog in town; warm and sunny in the back country.
Went to Dulzura Summit with family, Hop and Harriett. HKs and Holloways came out later. Hop and Doc. Holloway hunted.
Hunted both before and after lunch.
Went out at 10 AM. Returned at 6:30
Total miles 72.
Got 17 X.h., 3 Skellys, 2 Utas, 2 whiptails, 1 Hyla arenicolor. Lost many X.h. and 2 whiptails. Utas and Skellys not plentiful for so fine a day. Was surprised at this. Saw 1 orcutti.
Most of the Xantusias seemed to be on the north sides of boulders.
Saw no live snakes this day.
Dead snakes as follows:
At Dulzura
1 Red rattler larger
1 Pacific small.
2 gophers small.
At Jamul.
1 gopher large
(at Indian Springs)
At Jamacha 1 Red Rattler large.

Thursday, April 29, 1926

Friday , April 30, 1926

Page Edit History:

Saturday, May 1, 1926

Went to Descanso to see Allan. With Allison. 45 miles each way. 98 total. Went via highway. Started at 1:30 returned at 6:30.
A cold cloudy day without much wind. Beyond the willows the fog was quite heavy. Near Viejas grade so soacked as to be slippery.
One dead snake on the road.
A long nose at Flynn Springs. Got from Allan all caught at Willows.
1 orcutti, 6 Skellys, 1 uta, 1 small alligator.
Hunted (on return trip) in rocks near foot of new Viejas grade- that is in the dip. Got 13 X.h., 1 skink. Saw only one Skelly. Rocks were cold and wet. Xantusias extraordinarily easy to catch. Quite chilled and generally made no attempt to escape. Noted also that they frequently fell off the rock when the flake came away.
Got 2 Trimorphodons 1 large, 1 medium. Were in a crack in boulder. First one seen was only a few inches from below surface (on account of dark cloudy day ?) Rock was very large and took 2 of us a long time to pry away from main boulder.

Monday, May 17, 1926

Sunday continued

on another rock. Unfortunately one was seriously injured in turning over rock and died on the way in. Both were fine full grown specimens, noticeable for absence of white ring back of black head.

Hunted in the road about 2 miles north of Pine Valley Cuyamaca junction for a short time but got nothing here.

Then went to Pine Valley taking the north road and hunted in 2 locations. Got 3 Pacific Rattlers all in rocks and all seen by Allen first. 2 large; 1 medium. Plenty of lizards here particularly skellys and utas. No good takes for Xantusias. Total lizards.

1 Sceloporus orcutti
12 Sceloporus occidentalis biseriatus
2 Uta stansburiana hesperis
1 Phrynosoma (alive at Descanso
2 Xantusia henshawi (alive)
1 Gerrhonotus (small-alive)

Cowell brough in 547 newts, 3 gaites and 1 C. c. mormon tonight.

Got from Allen 3 Skellys and 1 Uta from hayuna? Also 2 large frogs. Rana aurora draytonii from Boudler creek

Saturday, May 22, 1926

A fine day, part cloudy in town, clear and moderately cool in the back country.

Went to Hurlburd's Grove alone; picked up Allen, then to Japatul and back. Went via old Viejas grade. Start at 12:45. Return at 6:05 Total miles 105.

Hunted only at one place about one mile south of old dobe house. At this point hunted about 3/4 hr. Got 1 Orcutti and 3 skellies. Saw several utas. No X. h. Probably had been buried over too recently.

Dead snakes
1 large gopher at Viejas
1 large Boyle's King at Bostonia (Dellmann)
1 Ring neck at Flynn Springs (saved spec).

Live snakes.
1 large banded racer at top of grade. Call it Descanso. But fiercely. Dived for him and him in bush by side of road
1 large Gopher as cut off turns to Hulburd. Was hurrying accross the road
1 large Garter after leaving Hulburd.
1 medium Boyle's King just south of Ellis Struck wildly before being touched at all. Fought hard
1 small mitchelli at Japatul.

lost one. Weather was clear and bright at this time.

<strike>Wednesday, May 26, 1926</strike>

Saturday, May 29 continued

On the way back when it was hotter not so many were seen.
On the way back coming up Mt. springs grade stopped to let the engine cool and got 1 Uta mearnsi. This was about half way up. did not stop any other place except to hunt the red racer. Returned to Jacumba at 3:30. It was warm but not oppressive.
After leaving family at Jacumba went back toward Mt. spring 4 miles and hunted in> along a rocky ridge covered with large boulders. This is a good place to hunt as the going is easy. Little bush. However there are no good snakes. Hunted here until 5:30. Not too hot for comfort.
Got 4 Uta mearnsi and 2 Uta stans. elegans? Saw many Uta mearnsi, 1 X.h.?, and a couple of skellies unidentified.
Uta mearnsi is certainly the common. Lot lizard here at this time of day. I saw not less than 25. They are wary and besides have to be hit in the head or they are lost. Saw one running along the underside of a boulder about 10 from the horizontal. Got a horned toad at Jacumba. Seems standard

Sunday, May 30, 1926

Went out alone at 7 AM; back at 8:30. Went to same rocks about 4 mi. east of Jacumba. First went to Desert View but nothing here.
At rocks got 11 Uta mearnsi, 6 Uta stansburiana elegans?, 1 gridiron tail. Latter was in sand bed of creek. Uta mearnsi even more plentiful than last night. Also saw several S. orcutti.
Got one large live mitchellii. Was moving in rocks. Evidently saw me first; gave characteristic rattle click. Got on small Hypsiglena dead on road. Saved specimen. Morning was rather warm. Hypsiglena evidently run over in the night.
Started for a drive at 10:30; returned at 4 P.M. Campo (Dewey) Morena Dam, Hurlburd's grove, back to Jacumba.
Miles 124.4-26.9= 97.5. Lunched at Buckmans. Did no hunting. Too hot.
1 large gopher dead on road at 62.2 Campo at 110.4 boulevard.
At 5:30 went to near rocks west of those stated in A.M. Saw a few Uta mearnsi, U. s. e. orcuttis and 1 Callisaurus. Got nothing

Monday, May 31, 1926

Started out at 6 AM alone. Went to the usual hunting ground 4 mi east of Jacumba. Returned to the hotel at 9:30. Worked hard amongst the rocks. Got about 20 Uta mearnsi. 2 Sceloporus orcutti and 2 Uta stansburiana sp. Saw 1 whiptail.
Uta mearnsi is unquestionably more plentiful in the morning than evening. Also Uta stansburiana. He latter are usually wild.
No snakes seen this A.M.
I am surprised at the lack of Xantusia henshawi in this rock ridge. Maybe Uta mearnsi drives them out. Opened up many favorable crevises without result. The one noted on Saturday may 29th was not certain; might have been a young Uta mearnsi.
Uta mearnsi is interesting to hunt. It is generally found in the large boulders. Is quite curious and consequently can be stalked easily. However they must be hit very hard (in the head) or they will get away. A large percentage are lost. The ones that are hit hard enough to get usually stick to the rock. When pushed these lizards

Page Edit History:
  • jrabbers 08/17/2011 12:58 PM
  • jrabbers 08/17/2011 12:58 PM

<strike>Tuesday, June 1, 1926</strike>

Monday May 31st continued

never seem to take refuge under ground as does Orcutti but jump from rock to rock until they find a suitable crevice. They are exceedingly plentiful at the proper time of morning. I must have seen at least 100 this A.M.
Started for home at 10:30 and reached home at 6 P.M. It was exceedingly hot east of the divide and quite warm elsewhere. Mostly too hot for snakes. Very few lizards were seen anywhere. 1 whiptail crossed the road near Buckmans another in San Felipe.
Took the following route home Jacumba (37.0), Hugh Bridge (50.9), Camp Junction (58.1), Pine Valley, Cuyamaca (ate lunch between Cuyamaca and Julian but did no hunting) Julian Junction (99.8), Banner, San Felipe, Warners, Santa Ysabel, Ramona, home (195.0).
Saw the following snakes:
1 large garter dead by the roadside at 50.0. Call it Hypass.
1 large Banded racer at Buckmans
1 medium Pacific rattler dead by roadside at Buckmans (67..4)
1 large Western yellow bellied racer dead by roadside at Cuyamaca
1 Arizona elegans dead by roadside at Warners (131.2)
1 Arizona elegans small dead by roadside at Warners (131.5)
1 Large gopher dead by the roadside at Witch Creek
1 Large Salvadora escaped at Witch Creek
Caught nothing in this trip.

Sunday, June 6, 1926

Went to Valley Center, Rincon, Pala, Bonsall, Escondido, Murphy Canyon with familly and Cotton kids. Started at 10:30; returned at 6:10. A cloudy day with a low mist in town. Elsewhere comfortably warm; rather too warm in Rincon. Total miles 131.5. If snakes came out on medium warm days in summer this would be a good day. Stopped for lunch 5 mi east of Pala on the river. This was the only stop. Hunted here about 2 hours. A good place for lizards. Shot 2 Skellies, Utas and Orcuttis. Caught one of the latter alive. X.h. negatus. Hunted mostly in dry bed of creek where there were many boulders. Got me live Gopher snake on the river bank. Quite a fighter. Had either been to the river to drink or had come across. Got an alligator at foot of Valley Center grade.
Dead Snakes. Long nose-Mission Valley
Red Racer 10.3- Rosedale
Patch nose 5 mi West of Pala
garter 8 mi do call it Bonsaler

July Monday 5, 1926

Went to Cuyamaca via Encanto, Spring Valley, Grossmont, Old Viejas Grade. Returned via Julian and Ramona. Total miles 131.7. Started at 9:30; returned at 6 PM. A rather warm day; although comfortable at Cuyamaca. With Family (ex. Alice)Stell and Dr. & Mrs. do Amaral. Lunched at point 1 mi north of Cuyamaca Dam. Hunted here in rock piles, both before and after lunch. Got one large C. oreganus; was stretched out under shade of a bush. Amaral picked him up by the tail. Bit himself several times.
Got 5 Utas and 1 Skelly. Saw plenty more of these.
Few lizards seen along the road and no live snakes. Evidently too hot.
Dead Snakes:
Rhinocheilus at Bostonia D.O.R.
do at Alpine do
Large mitchellii at Descanso do
(Top of Old Viejas Grade)

Page Edit History:

  • psully 11/23/2010 01:37 PM

Sunday July 18, 1926

3 PM to 5PM took venom from 37 snakes. Had better results holding them with with stick than with hands. Much quicker. Hand rather inconsistent results. Got plenty venom from some; not much from others.
15 C.oreganus
5 C. mitchellii
14 C. exsul
2 C oreganus? from Mojave Desert, Calif
1 C. oreganus from Arizona (not saved).

1926 Sunday 15, August

Took venom from 30 snakes. There were 4 new Pacifics and 1 new red. These gave much more venom than the old snakes. Many of the old snakes gave none at all. Some were evidently afflicted with some disease causing them to give a thick brown fluid instead of venom. Some gave this from only one gland - others from both.
Spent nearly all afternoon tagging spring specimens.

Saturday, November 27, 1926

Drove down from San Luis Obispo. A cold day after rain. All San Diego County driving at night. Saw nothing.

Page Edit History:
  • cassieswindle 08/11/2011 10:26 PM
  • psully 11/23/2010 01:37 PM

Sunday, November 28, 1926

Met Faldborg at the Zoo. He claims to have seen a den of C. mitchellii at the top of Mussey Grade on Armistice day. Says there were at least 20 in a horizontal cleft of a rock where they could not be reached. Returned Thanksgiving but they were further in; could be heard but only one could be seen.

Lampropeltis getula

California King snake

L.g. boylii refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a ringed pattern.

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
